        videoUrl: '/videos/consumer-protection/your-rights.mp4',
        videoType: 'mp4',
        transcript: 'In this final lesson of the Consumer Protection module, we\'ll cover your rights as an insurance consumer and how to file complaints when those rights are violated. Knowledge is power, and knowing your rights empowers you to stand up against unethical practices.\n\nLet\'s start with your fundamental consumer rights. First, you have the right to information - clear explanations of all policy terms, written documentation of everything discussed, disclosure of all fees and commissions, and adequate time to review before signing. No one can pressure you to sign immediately.\n\nYou have the right to privacy. This means control over your personal information, no sharing of data without consent, the right to know how your data is used, and protection under state and federal privacy laws.\n\nThe free look period is one of your most important rights. Every state mandates a period - typically 10 to 30 days - during which you can review your new policy and cancel for a full refund, no questions asked. Make sure you get this in writing and know the exact deadline.\n\nYou have the right to fair treatment. This includes no discrimination based on protected classes like race, gender, age, or disability. It means honest representation of products, no fraudulent or deceptive practices, and professional conduct at all times.\n\nSo when should you file a complaint? File if an agent made false promises or misrepresentations, forged your signature, sold you a policy you didn\'t authorize, failed to disclose important information, engaged in high-pressure tactics, churned your policies unnecessarily, or misappropriated your funds.\n\nHow do you file complaints? Your state\'s Insurance Department is the primary regulatory authority. They investigate consumer complaints and can impose serious penalties and sanctions. Most states allow you to file online or by mail.\n\nThe NAIC - National Association of Insurance Commissioners - maintains a national complaint database and coordinates multi-state issues. Visit naic.org to access their resources.\n\nIf securities are involved - such as variable life insurance or variable annuities - you can file with FINRA. They have an online complaint system at finra.org.\n\nThe Better Business Bureau creates a public complaint record, mediates disputes, and complaints affect business ratings.\n\nDocumentation is crucial. Keep all written communications, record dates and times of conversations, save emails and text messages, note names of everyone you speak with, and keep copies of all signed documents. Good documentation makes or breaks a complaint case.\n\nIf you\'ve suffered financial harm, you have legal options. Consult an attorney specializing in insurance law for significant cases. Consider arbitration or mediation for faster resolution. Small claims court works well for smaller amounts. If fraud is widespread, you might join or initiate a class action lawsuit.\n\nLet me walk you through the step-by-step complaint process. First, document everything before filing. Second, contact the company first - many states require you attempt direct resolution. Send a formal written complaint to their compliance department. Third, if they don\'t resolve it within 30 days, file with your state\'s Insurance Department. Fourth, follow up on your complaint and respond promptly to any requests for information.\n\nRemember, these complaint processes work. Agents do lose their licenses. Companies do get fined. Consumers do receive refunds and compensation. You have real power - don\'t be afraid to use it to protect yourself and other consumers.',
